Join the @skifastfoundation on Saturday, September 25th for the CureFest for Childhood Cancer walk in Vail. The SkiFast Foundation was founded by Vail Valley native and Ski and Snowboard Club Vail ski racer Campbell Sullivan in 2019, to raise awareness and provide scholarships to pediatric cancer patients to assist them in continuing their extracurricular passions. After a nearly four-year battle with a rare form of sarcoma, Campbell sadly passed away this past February. Campbell’s family, friends, and the Vail community are continuing her fight to find a cure.
All proceeds from the auction will go directly to SkiFast and assist in funding future scholarships. Follow the SkiFast Foundation for additional details on the walk and how to participate in the auction. 

Registration link: 
https://runsignup.com/Race/DC/Anywhere/VirtualCureFest2021?remMeAttempt=

(Or check my stories for a swipe up)

Thank you!
@curefestusa

node.text:
On this Father’s Day, my family, in collaboration with the @usskiteam, @usfreeskiteam, and @ussnowboardteam, is honored to announce that the Jeff Shiffrin Athlete Resiliency Fund will live on as a newly established need-based, direct-to-athlete funding source for U.S. Ski & Snowboard athletes. 
 
It has been amazing to hear all of your stories of resilience—your stories have offered endless inspiration and have kept my family going over the last year and a half. Dad would be so proud to see the way this fund has impacted athletes like @_tessjohnson, @hannah.g.halvorsen, @aaronblunck, @taylor_gold, and @devinlogan so far, and how it will continue to impact athletes for years to come. He was passionate about elite sport and there’s nothing he loved more than watching athletes overcome challenges and compete at the top of their game. Thank you.

Love, Mikaela 
 
Learn more/donate at keeptheflamealive.org. (*link in bio*)
#keeptheflamealive

Before the New Year, my fellow @kindnesswinsfoundation champions and I made a “Call for Kindness” to hear your stories about those who were especially kind in the last year. We had an outpouring of inspiring nominations, but today I am honored to announce that I’ve selected Breanna White to receive one of my 2020 Medals of Kindness.

Breanna is on the frontline of this global pandemic, working at  @saintalphonsus, outside in the snow, wind and rain, swabbing noses for COVID for months, in addition to her regular work in a children’s clinic. She has even taken on extra shifts while other medical staff in her midst have contracted COVID. Breanna was nominated because through it all, she always remained kind to her coworkers and her patients. 🤍

I know there are many more “Breanna’s” out there, sacrificing long days and harsh weather to keep us all safe through testing, and now, vaccinations. Please join me in thanking @breannalwhite for her dedication and feel free to tag someone in the comments who deserves recognition and their own "thank you" today! 🤗🤗

#kindnesswins 
#medalofkindness

I am SO excited to share that the Jeff Shiffrin Athlete Resiliency Fund has exceeded its funding goal. I am full of gratitude, first, for my teammates for being open and courageous as they shared their stories of resilience...and, of course, to @usskiteam and the donor families who worked tirelessly to make this Fund a reality.

Finally, I’m thankful to all of those who donated, sent words of encouragement, and shared their own stories of resilience via social media. It was really heartwarming to see all of the feedback, and I know my dad would have been so proud of this project and so excited to see athletes across U.S. Ski & Snowboard off to such a strong start this season. Thank you. 🙏 Learn more at keeptheflamealive.org. #keeptheflamealive

Join the @skifastfoundation on Saturday, September 25th for the CureFest for Childhood Cancer walk in Vail. The SkiFast Foundation was founded by Vail Valley native and Ski and Snowboard Club Vail ski racer Campbell Sullivan in 2019, to raise awareness and provide scholarships to pediatric cancer patients to assist them in continuing their extracurricular passions. After a nearly four-year battle with a rare form of sarcoma, Campbell sadly passed away this past February. Campbell’s family, friends, and the Vail community are continuing her fight to find a cure.
All proceeds from the auction will go directly to SkiFast and assist in funding future scholarships. Follow the SkiFast Foundation for additional details on the walk and how to participate in the auction. 

Registration link: 
https://runsignup.com/Race/DC/Anywhere/VirtualCureFest2021?remMeAttempt=

(Or check my stories for a swipe up)

Thank you!
@curefestusa

node.text:
Where were you,
When the planes hit?
When mass chaos erupted?
When thousands upon thousands died?
When we lost brothers, sisters, mothers, fathers, aunts, uncles, strangers?
When the first responders ran straight into the heat of the fire, and showed us all exactly where to find strength within ourselves at the exact moment we needed that most.
I was home. I was safe. I was comfortable. I was in 2nd grade. I was with my family. I didn’t understand the whole meaning of it, what it would bring.
20 years.
“This is the greatest nation on earth.”

Where are you,
Now?
Today?
We are out. They have traveled back in time, 20 years.
What have we left behind?
Is it good? Is it bad? I couldn’t begin to figure out how to decipher that.
Everybody has a different opinion. All of the opinions seem to make some sort of sense.
I am home. I am safe. I am comfortable. I am 26. I just returned from *ski camp*.
I have an education, and access to more if I so choose. I have freedom. I have opportunity. If you are reading this post, if you even have access to it, you probably do too.
20 years.
Where are we now?
Is this the greatest nation on earth?

A nation is nothing without the humans who make up that nation. 
It’s about the choices we make. The way we treat each other.

To the soldiers who have risked your lives, fought, died, and defended us for the last 20 years—our values, our freedoms, our opportunities, and defended those overseas—to give them more freedom, more opportunity, thank you.
To the unsung heroes, the victims and the first responders, who are still suffering from the terrors of that day 20 years ago.
You are everything.
Thank you.
I hope we in “the greatest nation” can find a real way to repay all of you and your families’ sacrifice, beyond a “thank you”.
I hope we find a way to better support the healing that you are still having to deal with…20 years later.
#NeverForget

node.text:
Wow. 🙏

$231k of 250k?! We are SO close to reaching our fundraising goal for the first round of direct-to-athlete grants through the Jeff Shiffrin Athlete Resiliency Fund. My family continues to be humbled by the generous support of the fund, and I know my dad would feel the same way. 

Thank you. 🤗

This extension of the fund that was established last year is near and dear to my heart because it connects so closely with the values my dad lived by. Thanks to both of my parents, our family strongly believes that great goals can be achieved through hard work, discipline, and resiliency. These direct-to-athlete, need-based grants will help U.S. Ski & Snowboard athletes on the cusp of breaking through to show the world what they can achieve on the big stage. Your support means so much. Thank you for continuing to #keeptheflamealive as we head into this important Olympic season, and for helping us reach the finish line. 

For more information or to donate, visit keeptheflamealive.org (link in bio). 🔥
